The Core Issue
The three properties come from three different studies, each measured at different temperature ranges:
PropertySourceTemperatures with direct measurementsDensityGopal & Rizvi, J. Indian Chem. Soc. 1966, 43, 179303, 313, 323, 333, 343, 353, 363 K (every 10 K from 30вҖ“90 В°C)Surface TensionMrad et al., J. Chem. Eng. Data 2022, 67, 2313283.15, 298.15, 313.15 K onlyHeat of VaporizationSmirnova et al., J. Chem. Thermodyn. 2007, 39, 1508Heat capacity data up to 340 K, but О”vapH derived at 298.15 K only

Answer
Mrad et al. (2022) measured surface tension of DMA at only three temperatures: 283.15, 298.15, and 313.15 K. ACS Publications This means 313.15 K is the only temperature above 300 K where surface tension is directly measured.
Smirnova et al. (2007) measured heat capacity of DMA up to 340 K by adiabatic vacuum calorimetry ScienceDirect, but their О”vapH is reported primarily at 298.15 K вҖ” values at other temperatures require derivation from the heat capacity data.
So strictly speaking, 313.15 K is the best candidate, but even there the Heat of Vaporization requires derivation rather than being a standalone direct measurement. There is no single temperature above 300 K in the literature where all three properties are available as independent, direct experimental single-point measurements from the same or different studies simultaneously вҖ” the Heat of Vaporization is consistently anchored to 298.15 K across all major sources.
Practical recommendation: Use 313.15 K for density (Gopal & Rizvi) and surface tension (Mrad et al.) as direct values, and derive О”vapH at 313.15 K from Smirnova et al.'s Cp data using Kirchhoff's law:
О”vapH(313В K)=О”vapH(298В K)+вҲ«298313О”CpвҖүdT\Delta_{vap}H(313\text{ K}) = \Delta_{vap}H(298\text{ K}) + \int_{298}^{313} \Delta C_p \, dTО”vapвҖӢH(313В K)=О”vapвҖӢH(298В K)+вҲ«298313вҖӢО”CpвҖӢdT
