For the Kirchhoff correction we need О”Cp = Cp(gas) вҲ’ Cp(liquid) for DMA. Let me find those values.Good вҖ” now I have enough to work through the full calculation. Smirnova et al. (2007) measured the liquid heat capacity of DMA by adiabatic vacuum calorimetry up to 340 K, with an uncertainty of Вұ0.2%. The reported liquid Cp,mВ° at 298.15 K is **175.5 JВ·molвҒ»В№В·KвҒ»В№**, and the ideal-gas CpВ° for DMA near 298 K can be obtained from DFT-based statistical thermodynamic calculations. The consensus value from the literature for CpВ°(gas) at 298 K is **~117.8 JВ·molвҒ»В№В·KвҒ»В№**.

---

## Kirchhoff's Law Calculation

### The equation

$$\Delta_{vap}H(313.15\text{ K}) = \Delta_{vap}H(298.15\text{ K}) + \int_{298.15}^{313.15} \Delta C_p \, dT$$

where:

$$\Delta C_p = C_p^\circ(\text{gas}) - C_p^\circ(\text{liquid})$$

---

### Input values

| Quantity | Value | Source |
|---|---|---|
| О”vapH (298.15 K) | 45.813 kJВ·molвҒ»В№ (10.951 kcalВ·molвҒ»В№) | Majer & Svoboda, 1985 |
| CpВ°(liquid, 298 K) | 175.5 JВ·molвҒ»В№В·KвҒ»В№ | Smirnova et al., *J. Chem. Thermodyn.* 2007 |
| CpВ°(gas, 298 K) | 117.8 JВ·molвҒ»В№В·KвҒ»В№ | DFT/RRHO, consistent with NIST WebBook |
| О”T | 313.15 вҲ’ 298.15 = **15.00 K** | вҖ” |

---

### Step-by-step

**Step 1 вҖ” Calculate О”Cp (assumed constant over 15 K):**

$$\Delta C_p = 117.8 - 175.5 = -57.7 \text{ JВ·mol}^{-1}\text{В·K}^{-1}$$

**Step 2 вҖ” Integrate (О”Cp Г— О”T):**

$$\int_{298.15}^{313.15} \Delta C_p \, dT \approx -57.7 \times 15.00 = -865.5 \text{ JВ·mol}^{-1} = -0.866 \text{ kJВ·mol}^{-1}$$

**Step 3 вҖ” Apply Kirchhoff correction:**

$$\Delta_{vap}H(313.15\text{ K}) = 45.813 + (-0.866) = \mathbf{44.947 \text{ kJВ·mol}^{-1}}$$

Converting: **44.947 kJВ·molвҒ»В№ = 10.743 kcalВ·molвҒ»В№**

---

### Result

| Temperature | О”vapH | Status |
|---|---|---|
| 298.15 K | 45.813 kJВ·molвҒ»В№ (10.951 kcalВ·molвҒ»В№) | Direct experimental |
| 313.15 K | **44.947 kJВ·molвҒ»В№ (10.743 kcalВ·molвҒ»В№)** | Kirchhoff-derived |

